                <head>163. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> delivered a radio and
                    television address to the American people from the Municipal Auditorium,
                    Oklahoma City, Oklahoma, on November 13, at 9:30 p.m. In his speech the
                    President discussed some of the actions in the national security area “to which
                    we must give our most urgent attention.” He specifically mentioned accelerating
                    the dispersal of Strategic Air Command to additional bases, providing facilities
                    for faster response to emergency alarm, development of an active missile defense
                    against missiles, additional funds for research on and testing of missiles,
                    increased pay to military personnel to make military careers more attractive,
                    possible cutbacks in some Federal civilian programs to maintain a balanced
                    budget, and consideration of proposals to strengthen scientific education and
                    basic research.</p>
                <p>The third draft of this speech, dated November 10, prepared by <persName
                        corresp="#p_LA1">Arthur Larson</persName>, Special Assistant to the
                    President, is attached to a memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_LA1"
                        >Larson</persName> to Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                        >Dulles</persName>, dated November 11, asking for the Secretary’s comments
                    on the draft. A handwritten note on <persName corresp="#p_LA1"
                    >Larson</persName>’s memorandum by Phyllis D. Bernau, <persName
                        corresp="#p_DAW1">Dulles</persName>’ personal assistant, reads: “Sec told to
                    ignore—I believe. PDB.” (Eisenhower Library, Dulles Papers)</p>
                <p>For text of the President’s speech, see <hi rend="italic">Public Papers of the
                        Presidents of the United States: <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Dwight D.
                            Eisenhower</persName>, 1957</hi>, pages 807–817.</p>
            </div>
